children.subject: I agree with this. Also, EE16A is a really fun class and, in my opinion, isn't as stressful as many of the CS classes I've taken. The staff tends to be helpful, kind, and almost desperate to make sure you understand everything and have a nice time! Also, the time commitment with Math 54 under your belt isn't too bad!
If you have taken Math 54, I actually recommend EE16a because the linear algebra portion (first half) may be a fun review

I'd suggest the latter. I took EECS 47D but still went to all the lectures and labs. The only thing I didn't do was the Module 1 HW's. 

Even if you've taken 54, the way linear algebra is taught is 16A is fast and different. Learning the same topic from a different perspective might help solidify your understanding of it.

Also, I'd say the 16A labs are quite important and worthwhile to attend while taking the class. You'll be applying linear algebra concepts you've learned to actual situations, which is a

different experience from Math 54.

If you take EECS 47D, you aren't officially enrolled in a lab, so if it gets crowded, you'll be kicked out (this happened to me and finding a lab was overall a hassle). 

I'd recommend taking EE 16A.

history.content: So I have a choice of taking EECS 47D or EE16A (P/NP), and I was just wondering if anyone could offer advice as to which one they would recommend I take? Thank you!
